items.description:
This beginners class will introduce you to Inkscape, a free 2D design program used to create digital art for web or print, which can also be used to make things with Technocopia's laser and vinyl cutters. By the end of this 2 hour session, you will have made your first work of digital art!

Things We'll Cover:

- Introduction to the interface, tools and drop down menus
- Working with basic shapes to make a scene
- Understanding paths and nodes and how to manipulate them
- The differences between pencil tool, pen tool and brush tool
- How to personalize the side bar
- How to use the text tool
- Fun with filters
- File saving and sharing

Computers will be provided. Need help installing Inkscape on your own computer? Feel free to bring it along and we'll help!

This class is ages 16+. Youth aged 12-15 may attend for free, but must be accompanied by a paying adult.

Visit the Inkscape homepage here: https://inkscape.org/en/

PLEASE NOTE: Registration via Eventbrite is preferred to ensure a seat in the class, however, if you wish to pay by cash or check, please notify us immediately at info@technocopia.org.
Eventrbite link for registering:
https://www.eventbrite.com/e/digital-design-for-makers-inkscape-basics-tickets-48298746852

items.description:
Laser cutters are used to produce precise cuts and engravings with several materials based on 2D vector and raster images. The machines are commonly used for anything from industrial manufacturing to small and intricate art projects. This class will teach how to operate Technocopia’s Full Spectrum laser cutter safely and effectively. Students will learn the process of creating and preparing a simple design in Inkscape, opening it in Retina Engrave, and then operating the laser to produce the cut. We will also learn how to calibrate the auto focus sensor, and discuss what types of materials are appropriate to use with the machine.


This tool is available for family use! Any youth between the ages of 12-17 may take this class with a participating adult. For our student registration form and for class policies, please visit: http://technocopia.org/tool-training/. 


To register on Eventbrite please visit this link here:
https://www.eventbrite.com/e/tool-training-laser-cutter-tickets-59529608662


About the Instructor

Adam Zelny is a multimedia designer and educator in the fields of 2D and 3D CAD, digital fabrication, audio and video production, music, and design oriented art. As a part of Technocopia's administration team, he has helped build the education platform for tool training and workshop programs, and actively teaches classes for laser cutter and 3D printer workflows. His role as an educator involves incorporating art into STEM oriented classes, crafting professional development workshops for fellow teachers, and using digital fab tools to learn and make useful things that look good. As a former board member, Adam played a role in relocating and expanding Technocopia's facility and programs, and continues to volunteer his time to growing the makerspace. Adam thinks that sci-fi is a great genre, and enjoys the occasionally good video game.

items.description:
This class is for people with little to no sewing machine experience. Students will learn the parts of a sewing machine, how to thread, operate and maintain machine, and how to use the tools available in the sewing area of the textile studio at Technocopia. The students will learn on a Singer Heavy Duty 4423 machine the following: power on/off, pedal attachment, backstitch button, handwheel operation, winding bobbins, loading bobbins, threading machine, changing needles, safe cutting with rotary mats and rulers, simple maintenance of machines, stitch and tension adjustments, and shop standards of cleanliness and organization.

The practice project for this class will be the creation of a small credit or business card wallet. A small selection of free fabric is available to students for this project, but students are also welcome to bring in their own piece of quilters cotton (¼ of yard will be plenty) if they prefer.

Successful completion of this class will result in certification of Technocopia members to use the sewing machines in the textile studio. For members with more advanced sewing experience, contact annie.stegink@technocoipa.org to discuss a more appropriate certification process.

items.description:
**This class has a prerequisite. See below** A serger is a machine that uses up to four threads to sew a seam, cut off the raw edges, and finish the edges in a neat stitch pattern all at the same time. This class is for people with little to no serger experience, however students must have sewing machine skills (see below for more details). Students will learn the parts of a serger and how to thread, operate, and maintain the serger machine. The practice project for this class will be the creation of a tool roll up pouch. A small selection of free fabric is available to students for this project, but students are also welcome to bring in their own piece (1/2 yd) of heavy, stiff fabric (such as home decor fabric, duck canvas, or a heavy cotton) if they prefer. **In order to take this class, students must have successfully passed the sewing machine tool training at Technocopia** Successful completion of this class will result in certification of Technocopia members to use the serger machine in the textile studio. For members with more advanced serging experience, contact annie.stegink@technocoipa.org BEFORE signing up for serger class to discuss an alternative certification process.

items.description:
This class will teach you how to use our new Tippmann Boss Leather Stitcher and Hand Press to make a variety of leather projects in our new textiles studio. Each student will learn how to wind a bobbin, thread, and operate the Tippmann Boss, as well as learning the basics at using the hand press to install snaps, rivets, and more. These tools can be used to make many interesting leather projects including wallets, cuff bracelets, knife sheaths, and more. Each student will practice their new skills by making keychains that will include some stitching and a snap or rivet.

No experience is needed for this class, and successful completion of the class results in tool certification for using the Tippmann Boss and hand press at Technocopia. For non-members, this makes students eligible to participate in upcoming project based classes, and for members, this results in free use of the machines during their membership hours.

items.description:
We are excited to offer a night of socializing, stitching, and learning new skills with our Visible Mending Sip and Stitch Workshop! 


Patching holes and mending tears can be a form of art using embroidery thread, colorful fabric, and a variety of decorative stitches. Bring an item or two that you would like to jazz up (they don’t have to be in need of repair- decorative stitching can be used to brighten any old shirt, jeans, or jacket), and we will provide the rest! 

Each ticket includes light munchies, embroidery floss, needles, a small assortment of fabric, and basic instruction. Participants should bring at least 2 articles of clothing they would like to stitch, and any particular fabric they would like to use for patches, if desired. Participants are welcome to bring their own wine or beer to sip as they stitch!

This event is for ages 21+. No experience necessary.

Home School Program:
Utilizing special lab techniques students will culture bacteria and fungus on selected nutrient mediums to create  colorful pallets and pictures in petri dishes. A popular art trend  among some microbiologists, students will learn how to cultivate  micro-organisms, prepare nutrient agars and petri dishes and exercise creative license in designing abstract and real to life images on their cultured dishes. Students will record their art through photography. 


This class satisfies the following biology topics:Biological Classification, Cell Cycle & Division, Microbiology Technique & Procedure

Cost: $80

This Monday class, 10:00am - 3:30pm, meets weekly a total of 4 times,  Sept. 9th - Sept.30th. Single class semester tuition is $250 and it covers all tuition and material costs. 

Class Description:

This class celebrates the intersection of chemistry and craft. WPI Professor of Chemistry, Dr. Grimm, and Technocopia glass artist, Molly Jackson, will work alongside one another to bring the chemical and artistic properties of glass in full light. Students can expect to gain an understanding of glass within; states of matter and thermodynamics, atomic and molecular components, ionic compounds and crystallization, and color and light. Students will learn the art of flameworking and how to use the glass shop and its tools properly and safely. Students will spend 2.5 hours with each instructor (Dr. Grimm and Ms. Jackson) every Monday, to engage in a chemistry lesson and lab, and work on glass studio projects. Students will have 30 min. between classes for lunch.

Instructors: Dr. Ronald Grimm and Molly Jackson
Event Link: https://www.eventbrite.com/e/glass-chemistry-craft-tickets-67658290769

Class Description:
A Makerspace is a place where people get together to learn, explore, share ideas, and make things. It is a learning-by-doing experience and this class is designed to help teenagers explore Technocopia’s resources to do just that! The only prerequisite is curiosity and a desire to make things!
This course is a great starting point for exploring fabrication techniques and the skills to use them. Ideas, skills and projects will evolve as students explore and tinker using both low and high tech tools. We will explore the resources available at Technocopia including various tools used in areas of woodworking, textiles, and digital fabrication. This class will include a focus on design and creation of several small-scale projects. Collaboration and sharing will be encouraged in the development of these projects and we will employ aspects of design thinking in the generation and implementation of them. This class will include wood working, sewing, computer aided design, and use of a vinyl and laser cutter. This course is specifically designed to suit students aged 10-13.
Instructor: Jessica Sadlier

This Wednesday class, 11:30am - 1:00pm, meets weekly a total of 12 times, Sept. 11th - Dec. 4th. No class on 11/27. Single class semester tuition is $325 and covers all tuition and material costs. A non-refundable deposit of $75 reserves a seat in this class.
Ages 10-13
Class Description:
Caldecott Award stories are the springboard for introducing units of studies where students will write both analytically and creatively. This semester we’ll read and analyze short stories and poems and engage in friendly active discussions. Students will work to write well crafted and well researched essays with attention to clear and grammatically correct writing. Building on this clarity of thought, students will be challenged to think deeply and write about themselves and topics important to them in descriptive, logical and evocative ways. Grammar, mechanics and usage as well as research skills will be taught. This semester students can expect to write poetry, descriptive essays, narrative essays and research and write reports. Because language arts lessons focus so intensely on words we will also look to art, drama, music, movement and observation of the natural world as key ingredients to building openings for developing writers to safely experiment with writing technique.
Instructor: Cindy Nordstrom

Sign up here:

https://www.eventbrite.com/e/caldecott-writing-tickets-68009695831

Class Description:
This fun and challenging course will bring the fascinating ancient world of Early Crete to the Last Roman Emperor to vivid life. Students will weave together strands from lectures and projects in geography, mythology, art, music, poetry, engineering, dance, and drama to immerse themselves in the meaning and importance of this time period.
This course will include the study of primary source material and important literary works of the time. Maps, timelines, and outlines, are incorporated into the student’s weekly work and students are expected to perform research and write reports. By the end of this dynamic course, students will be able to draw connections from our readings, lectures and projects to the continuing story of our world.
Instructor: Cindy Nordstrom

Single class semester tuition is $325 and covers all tuition and material costs. A non-refundable deposit of $75 reserves a seat in this class. Writing, History & Tech Wednesday packages are still available.
Ages 10-13
Class Description:
This fun and challenging course will bring the fascinating ancient world of Early Crete to the Last Roman Emperor to vivid life. Students will weave together strands from lectures and projects in geography, mythology, art, music, poetry, engineering, dance, and drama to immerse themselves in the meaning and importance of this time period.
This course will include the study of primary source material and important literary works of the time. Maps, timelines, and outlines, are incorporated into the student’s weekly work and students are expected to perform research and write reports. By the end of this dynamic course, students will be able to draw connections from our readings, lectures and projects to the continuing story of our world.
Instructor: Cindy Nordstrom

items.description:
In this class you will learn the basics of making patterns for your costumes based on the actual wearer. We will explore techniques that will allow you to create shape-conforming garments and coverings for any shape, not just bodies but also furniture or equipment. We will also discuss adding design details to your patterns and adjusting the fit of the finished project. You will leave this class with patterns you can use over and over again.

https://www.eventbrite.com/e/intro-to-custom-patternmaking-tickets-72631361357

Discover how easy it is to make costumes that defy gravity!  Learn techniques to create volume using various interfacings and linings. We will discuss using wire, foam and other materials to create a support structure for your costumes while still keeping them lightweight and comfortable to wear.

Sign up on Eventbrite here:
https://www.eventbrite.com/e/costume-engineering-tickets-72635529825

Start with ready-to-wear clothing and hack your way to a quick and easy costume with little to no sewing. Learn how to turn a few adult t-shirts into a child's cloak, a ninja costume, or a fairy outfit. Paint, glue and duct tape can transform plain basics into fun costumes, add some trims and embellishments and you've got a quick, easy one-of-a kind creation.

Sign Up here on Eventbrite here:
https://www.eventbrite.com/e/hack-yourself-a-costume-tickets-72636426507

items.description:
This beginners class will introduce you to Inkscape, a free 2D design program used to create digital art for web or print, which can also be used to make things with Technocopia's laser and vinyl cutters. This class focuses on how to process a digital file so it may be cut on a Roland vinyl cutter to produce a sticker.

In this vinyl cutter class we will cover:

- Learning about the different types of vinyl
- Understanding the mechanics of the vinyl cutter
- Setting up an Inkscape design for printing
- Testing different vinyls and changing settings
- Weeding the excess vinyl using special tools
- Applying transfer tape to design

Computers will be provided. Need help installing Inkscape on your own computer? Feel free to bring it along and we'll help!

This class is ages 16+. Youth aged 12-15 may attend for free, but must be accompanied by a paying adult.

Visit the Inkscape homepage here: https://inkscape.org/en/


PLEASE NOTE: Registration via Eventbrite is preferred to ensure a seat in the class, however, if you wish to pay by cash or check, please notify us immediately at info@technocopia.org. Thank you!


Eventbrite link for sign up here:
https://www.eventbrite.com/e/digital-design-for-makers-vinyl-cutter-tickets-73485124987

About the Instructor

Breanna Niebel is a graphic designer and animator with extensive background in creative software. She went to college in Vermont and attended grad school in Wales, United Kingdom. Her passions include animation, drawing, and learning new things. Breanna has used Inkscape to design and laser cut wooden earrings, which she now sells on her Etsy page.

items.description:
Learn necessary foundations in general chemistry while also gaining lab experience. Taught in partnership with MCPHS!

This is a six class session, and runs Thursdays, 10am-12pm, from 10/3 - 11/7. Cost of $29 covers tuition and all materials. Take advantage of this great chemistry offer!
This class is designed for students with some, little, or no former experience with chemistry. Concepts introduced will include: the periodic table, atomic models, chemical reactions, and balancing equations. These concepts, along with the lab technique introduced, are a necessary foundation to later applications in general and advanced chemistry. All classes include hands on learning and/or science laboratories, with optional take home assignments and articles to suit your home school education plan. Lab titles for this class are the following: A Qualitative Analysis of Ions, Everyday pH Testing, and Water Quality. Daily discussions will make important connections to

everyday events and relevant and current topics.


Designed for ages 11-17. Students will be broken into lab groups by age and skill level. This is a six class session, and runs Thursdays, 10am-12pm, from 10/3 - 11/7.


Sign up on Eventbrite here:
https://www.eventbrite.com/e/chemistry-basics-tickets-73493716685
items.location: Technocopia, 44 Portland St, Worcester, MA 01608, USA
